# Coding Standards

- Keep files under 300 lines (hard limit 400). Extract composables, sub-components, helpers, or utilities when approaching the limit.
- Make code modular. Separate logic into reusable, well-named files and folders.
- Before writing new code, search for existing implementations — reuse before creating.
- Duplicated logic across files MUST be extracted into a shared module.

## Code Quality

- Prefer the simplest solution that works — do not add abstractions, wrappers, or patterns beyond what the task requires.
- Prefer immutability — use spread operators or new arrays/objects instead of mutating in place.
- Use early returns to avoid deep nesting. Guard clauses at the top, happy path at the bottom.
- Extract magic numbers and strings into named constants.
- Run independent async operations in parallel with `Promise.all` (JS/TS) or equivalent patterns.
- Comments should explain WHY, not narrate WHAT. If the code needs a comment to explain what it does, simplify the code instead.

## Bugfixing Mode

When the task is a bugfix:
- Minimize changes — do not refactor unrelated code.
- Do small iterations to avoid breaking things.
- Summarize what you changed and why.
- Do not change the UI unless necessary to fix the bug.
